{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501787"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:33:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:33:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1790"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1790"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.4,0.04,0.01,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77793"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1790"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63312"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"2852"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26665"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77793"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a four-day history of severe pain in his right knee, which started soon after a weekend of heavy alcohol intake. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 128/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His right knee is swollen, warm, and erythematous. Range of motion is limited by pain, but he is able to flex the knee to 45 degrees and fully extend it. There is no laxity on anterior drawer test. There are white, chalky subcutaneous nodules over his left elbow and on his hands. An aspirate of the right knee is performed and shows negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings would most strongly support the diagnosis in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Presence of fever and elevated white cell count","Calcium pyrophoshate crystals","Erythematous rash with silvery scales","History of recent gastrointestinal infection","Tophi containing monosodium urate crystals"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of gout including acute monoarthritis following alcohol consumption (a known trigger) and the presence of tophi. The synovial fluid analysis showing negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals confirms the diagnosis of gout. \u003Cstrong\u003ETophi containing monosodium urate crystals\u003C/strong\u003E are pathognomonic for chronic gout, representing deposits of urate crystals in soft tissues that appear as white, chalky nodules as seen in this patient\u0027s elbow and hands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresence of fever and elevated white cell count\u003C/strong\u003E may occur in both gout and septic arthritis. While these findings wouldn\u0027t exclude gout, they are non-specific and could suggest infection, making them less useful diagnostically than tophi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium pyrophosphate crystals\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of pseudogout (calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease). These crystals appear positively birefringent and rhomboid-shaped under polarised microscopy, in contrast to the negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals seen in gout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythematous rash with silvery scales\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of psoriasis and may be associated with psoriatic arthritis. This finding would point away from rather than support a diagnosis of gout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistory of recent gastrointestinal infection\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest reactive arthritis, which typically presents with the triad of arthritis, urethritis, and conjunctivitis following a gastrointestinal or genitourinary infection. This history would not support a diagnosis of gout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of gout is definitively made by identifying monosodium urate crystals in synovial fluid or tophaceous material. Risk factors include male sex, obesity, alcohol consumption, diuretic use, and foods high in purines. The presence of tophi indicates chronic gout with prolonged hyperuricaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The finding of negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals in synovial fluid is diagnostic of gout.","Gout can present with tophi, which are deposits of monosodium urate crystals in soft tissues.","Alcohol intake can precipitate gout attacks due to increased uric acid production."],"references":["Dalbeth N, Merriman TR, Stamp LK. Gout. Lancet. 2016 Oct 22;388(10055):2039-2052. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(16)00346-9. Epub 2016 Apr 21. PMID: 27112094.","Chhana A, Dalbeth N. The gouty tophus: a review. Curr Rheumatol Rep. 2015 Mar;17(3):19. doi: 10.1007/s11926-014-0492-x. PMID: 25761926.","Hainer BL, Matheson E, Wilkes RT. Diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of gout. Am Fam Physician. 2014 Dec 15;90(12):831-6. PMID: 25591183."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63312"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1790"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"ty